  "text": "The `acks` producer configuration value propagates through the Kafka codebase as follows:\n\n## 1. Configuration Definition and Validation\n\n**ProducerConfig.java** (lines 123, 383-388, 639-645): Defines the ACKS_CONFIG constant with the default value \"all\" and validates input values (0, 1, -1, \"all\"). The parseAcks() method converts \"all\" to \"-1\" and validates numeric values.\n\n## 2. Producer Initialization\n\n**KafkaProducer.java** (line 526): During producer initialization, the acks value is read from the configuration, parsed as a short, and passed to the Sender constructor: `short acks = Short.parseShort(producerConfig.getString(ProducerConfig.ACKS_CONFIG));`\n\n## 3. Produce Request Building\n\n**Sender.java** (lines 98-99, 148, 856-864, 897-904): The Sender class stores the acks value as a private final field and uses it when building ProduceRequest objects. The sendProduceRequests() method iterates through collated batches and calls sendProduceRequest() with the acks parameter. The sendProduceRequest() method creates a new ProduceRequest using ProduceRequestData().setAcks(acks).\n\n## 4. Protocol Encoding\n\n**ProduceRequest.json** (lines 54-56): The protocol schema defines the Acks field as \"int16\" with versions \"0+\", documenting that it represents \"The number of acknowledgments the producer requires the leader to have received before considering a request complete.\"\n\n**ProduceRequest.java** (lines 91, 104, 193-195): The ProduceRequest class extracts the acks value from ProduceRequestData in its constructor and stores it as a private field, providing a getter method to access it.\n\n## 5. Broker-Side Request Handling\n\n**KafkaApis.scala** (lines 485-487, 499, 537): The broker receives the ProduceRequest and uses the acks value to:\n- Determine throttling behavior (request quota is exempted when acks == 0)\n- Decide whether to send a response (no response is sent when acks == 0)\n- Pass the requiredAcks value to ReplicaManager.handleProduceAppend()\n\n## 6. Replica Manager Processing\n\n**ReplicaManager.scala** (lines 732, 799, 916-920, 1355-1365): The ReplicaManager receives requiredAcks in handleProduceAppend() and:\n- Validates the acks value (0, 1, or -1) using isValidRequiredAcks()\n- Determines if a delayed produce operation is needed using delayedProduceRequestRequired(), which checks if acks == -1\n- Passes requiredAcks to appendRecords() and creates ProduceMetadata for delayed operations\n\n## 7. Partition Leader Write Acknowledgment\n\n**Partition.scala** (line 1370): In appendRecordsToLeader(), the partition leader checks `if (inSyncSize < minIsr && requiredAcks == -1)` to enforce min ISR constraints when acks == -1 (strongest durability guarantee).\n\n## 8. Delayed Produce Operation\n\n**DelayedProduce.scala** (lines 43-46, 89-117): The DelayedProduce class stores produceRequiredAcks in ProduceMetadata and monitors replication progress via checkEnoughReplicasReachOffset(). It completes when either:\n- All required replicas have reached the required offset (used when acks == -1)\n- A partition error occurs\n- The operation times out\n\nThe complete flow ensures that the acks value controls write durability semantics: acks=0 provides no guarantees with fire-and-forget semantics, acks=1 guarantees the leader has written to its local log, and acks=-1 (\"all\") guarantees all in-sync replicas have written the data before acknowledging."
